1.

Requirement:
“Provide ability to view vendor information easily.”

Ambiguity (Unambiguity):

“easily”

Why:

“Easily” depends on the user. One person might expect a search bar, another might expect filters or a dashboard. Since it’s not defined, developers won’t know what to build.
2.

Requirement:
“System should support quick invoice processing.”

Ambiguity (Unambiguity):

“quick”

Why:

“Quick” has no specific time attached to it. Without a defined timeframe (like seconds or minutes), there’s no way to tell if the system meets the requirement.
3.

Requirement:
“Allow users to manage payments efficiently.”

Ambiguity (Meaningfulness):

“manage”

Why:

“Manage” is too broad—it could mean creating payments, editing them, approving them, or deleting them. The system can’t implement a clear function if the action itself isn’t defined.
4.

Requirement:
“Provide reports for financial tracking.”

Ambiguity (Completeness):

“reports”

Why:

It doesn’t say what kind of reports are needed (e.g., summary, detailed, monthly). Without that, the requirement is incomplete and open to interpretation.
5.

Requirement:
“Enable handling of different types of invoices.”

Ambiguity (Completeness):

“different types of invoices”

Why:

The requirement never specifies what those types are (e.g., recurring, one-time, credit invoices). Developers won’t know what cases the system needs to support.
6.

Requirement:
“System should allow updates to account details when needed.”

Ambiguity (Unambiguity):

“when needed”

Why:

There’s no clear rule for when updates are allowed. This could lead to inconsistent behavior or security issues because “need” isn’t defined.
7.

Requirement:
“Support integration with other systems if possible.”

Ambiguity (Meaningfulness):

“if possible”

Why:

This makes the requirement unclear because it doesn’t commit to anything. It’s not clear whether integration is required or optional, so it’s hard to prioritize or implement.
8.

Requirement:
“Provide notifications for important events.”

Ambiguity (Unambiguity):

“important”

Why:

What counts as “important” can vary (e.g., overdue payments vs. new invoices). Without defining this, the system may notify too much or too little.
9.

Requirement:
“Allow users to access data securely.”

Ambiguity (Completeness):

“securely”

Why:

It doesn’t specify how security should be handled (e.g., encryption, authentication). Without details, developers can’t ensure the system meets the expected level of security.
10.

Requirement:
“Maintain accurate financial records.”

Ambiguity (Unambiguity):

“accurate”

Why:

“Accurate” isn’t defined—there’s no rule for how correctness is measured or validated, so it’s unclear what standard the system must meet.
